\xe3\x83\xbb\xe3\x83\xbb\xe3\x83\xbb
An extremely joyous occasion for @sandeepjavelin, @SuyashNJadhav , and Manish Narwal on being conferred the prestigious Arjuna Award by the Honourable President of India.

After the disappointment in Rio, Sandeep broke multiple records in Javelin throw in the F46 category. He made India proud by winning the gold medal by breaking his own world record at the World Para Athletics Championships in Dubai. 

Suyash Jadhav won three medals at the 2018 Asian Para Games in Jakarta and became the first Indian to win a gold medal in swimming at the Asian Para Games.

The 17-year-old Manish Narwal  surprised everyone with his sharp shooting skills just months after stepping onto the range three years ago, and in 2019 he won the silver medal for India at the World Shooting Para Sport World Cup in Croatia. This achievement of his secured a quota for India at the 2021 Paralympics that will be held in Tokyo. 

The trio is supported in their journeys through the Para Champions Programme, which is in association with Principal  Partners - @indusind_bank , Associate Partners AT&T, @sonypicturesnetworks and Bry Air.
 
#parachampions #arjunaawards #nationalsportsday #2020 #sports #paralympics #parasports'

b'Meet Melon Soy Murum - a physically challenged, marginal farmer, in the tribal village of Binda, in the Murhu block of Jharkhand. His disability makes cultivating his land extremely difficult. In ordinary times, he would resort to tailoring as an alternate source of income to support his family of six, which includes an elderly mother and three small children. While unseasonable rainfall affected his farm produce, the sudden lockdown, because of COVID-19, disrupted his livelihood from tailoring.

This brought a ray of hope to Melon Soy Murum, who had purchased a sewing machine just last year. WOTR trained him on how to stitch masks and provided the material to stitch the masks for distribution among villagers. Melon received Rs.7 per mask he stitched. Within seven days, he completed 376 masks and earned Rs.2632. Unlike in urban centers, in the tribal villages of Jharkhand, where people have very basic needs, this amount provides for a dignified subsistence.

Through the immediate COVID-19 relief operation, IndusInd Bank has supported livelihood for 213 Self Help Group (SHG) members through the activity of stitching masks for distribution among villagers. This has happened in the villages of three states of Jharkhand, Odisha, and Maharashtra, in which IndusInd Bank\xe2\x80\x99s Watershed Development Programme is ongoing. Through the SHG Members, 47,800 masks have been stitched and distributed to community members till date.

Kitchen gardens here are estimated to have fed over 1,500 people during the lockdown. Seeds and training on how to grow organic vegetables are provided to volunteers like Saraswati as part of an initiative supported by IndusInd Bank @indusind_bank and implemented by WOTR @wotr.india Maharastra. Our masked crusaders aka #COVIDHeroes from Osmanabad, Maharashtra are hard at work on their sewing machines. b'#Repost @hindujafoundation

Sometimes, your #COVIDHero may just be a voice on the phone. When a call came in from a remote village in Bhopal to Bharat Sanjeevani\xe2\x80\x99s helpline, little did the executive on call expect to be talking to a pregnant woman looking for advice on delivery! Some quick thinking by the customer service executive and the call was directed to the right officials, and the expectant mother got the help she needed. This is just one of the many heart-warming stories coming in from Bharat Sanjeevani\xe2\x80\x99s call-centre team, which is currently helping the Madhya Pradesh state government during the COVID-19 crisis. During non-lockdown times, the BFIL (Bharat Financial Inclusion Limited) team runs a doorstep veterinary services helpline that farmers across MP can access by dialing 1962. But seeing the increased load placed by the pandemic on government health services like the 104 helpline, #BFIL stepped in and offered their services. The CSOs or customer service order professionals were quick to adapt to the guidelines and handle distress and emergency calls. To date, they have handled over 3,000 calls helping people report suspected cases of COVID-19, access relief material and rations through the PDS scheme, request an ambulance and seek help, in the case of migrants and others unable to return home.

Johan Ham Soy is a trained community worker aka a Vasundhara Sevak aka a #COVIDHero. He hails from the remote village of Gullu in Jharkhand, where he who works with the watershed project funded by IndusInd Bank @indusind_bank. Gullu, like many other villages during the pandemic, has witnessed \xe2\x80\x98reverse migration\xe2\x80\x99 with many students and seasonal workers returning in large numbers before the nationallockdown. The local administration had its task cut out trying to identify those who need to be quarantined. This is where Johan stepped up. He used a network of informants to isolate 14 people from Gullu, who needed to be tested or placed in quarantine. Luckily, none of them tested positive. But without the efforts of aware and alert citizens like Johan, the administration would not be able to do its job in keeping people safe. When he was commended for a job well done, Johan said, if not me, then who? Spoken like a true hero.

b'#repost \xe2\x80\xa2 @hindujafoundation Did you know that more than half of India lives in \xe2\x80\x98water-stressed\xe2\x80\x99 regions? These are places where the need is greater than the land can provide, and what water there is may not be fit to drink. Recognising the urgency of this crisis, our Foundation has adopted water stewardship as a flagship theme shared across Hinduja group companies.
